<div id="how-to-write-your-newsletter"></div>
<h2>How to write a newsletter</h2>
<p>Crafting the perfect newsletter involves many details and moving parts, so to focus on the essence, weâ€™ll distill it down to the key elements of a good-performing newsletter: subject line, preview text, introduction, email copy, graphics, and layout, calls to action, and footer elements. You may opt to use AI to help you write your newsletter&#8211;or you might want to create it on your own! You can move forward either way with these steps&#8211;just make sure to edit any AI-generated copy for accuracy and tone.</p>
<div id="determine-the-topic-for-your-newsletter"></div>
<h3>1. Determine the topic(s) for your newsletter</h3>
<p>Your newsletter is your chance to build a strong, meaningful connection with your customers. For small businesses, it is a unique opportunity to stay in front of customers without navigating social media and search engine algorithms, where they have to compete against some of the biggest brands. <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/email-marketing-trends-2025/">Email marketing</a> puts you on a level playing field, and itâ€™s only up to your creativity whether youâ€™ll get noticed.</p>
<p>But hereâ€™s the thing: Itâ€™s not about selling every second. You need to offer value to your customers. Whether itâ€™s useful tips, behind-the-scenes peeks, or solving a problem they didnâ€™t even know they had, your <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/monthly-email-newsletter-ideas/">newsletter ideas</a> should speak directly to your audience&#8217;s needs and interests, not just your latest product launch. Keep it fresh and relevant so people actually look forward to reading your emails.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-topics-example-penguin.webp" alt="newsletter topic example from penguin" width="900" height="755" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-93047" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-topics-example-penguin.webp 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-topics-example-penguin-480x403.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Here are 10 <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/02/25/email-newsletter-ideas">ideas for your next newsletter</a>:</p>
<ul>
<li>How-to newsletter</li>
<li>A roundup of helpful blog posts</li>
<li>Gift guides</li>
<li>A thank you email from the CEO</li>
<li>Behind-the-scenes content</li>
<li>Interview with an expert</li>
<li>Hacks and unexpected ways to use your product</li>
<li>Customer stories and reviews</li>
<li>A poll or survey</li>
<li>Tip of the week/month</li>
</ul>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4eb.png" alt="ðŸ“«" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Get everything you need for great emails &gt;&gt;</strong> <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/email-examples-and-templates?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_Email_EmailTemplates_Download&amp;itm_source=wordstream&amp;itm_medium=blog&amp;itm_campaign=incontent_links">The Complete Email Marketing Toolkit: Free Email Templates, Subject Lines &amp; Tips</a></p>
<div id="draft-a-hook-worthy-introduction"></div>
<h3>2. Draft a hook-worthy introduction</h3>
<p>Once subscribers open your <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/email-marketing-checklist/">email marketing newsletter</a>, the introduction or hook is your chance to grab their attention from the get-go. Whether you use a bold statement, a surprising fact, or an intriguing question, make it something that piques readersâ€™ curiosity and makes them think, â€œI need to know more.â€ You can also use humor as a way to show your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/03/31/brand-personality-messaging">brand personality</a> and make your newsletter more relatable.</p>
<p>But remember: the introduction is setting the tone for whatâ€™s next. If your intro promises something exciting, your content better deliver.</p>
<div id="close-out-with-a-strong-call-to-action"></div>
<h3>3. Close out with a strong call to action</h3>
<p>Youâ€™ve created the perfect hook with the introduction and your newsletter content is exciting and engagingâ€”great job! The question the reader has is: â€œWhatâ€™s next?â€ If you donâ€™t provide a clear <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/10/09/call-to-action">call to action</a>, you leave readers hanging.</p>
<p>To capitalize on the momentum, make sure you use a strong call to action. Whether checking out a product, reading a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/04/06/irresistible-blog-post-titles">blog post</a>, or signing up for an event, make it clear and easy to follow.</p>
<p>When announcing their new collection, Cotopaxi used a straightforward call to action for subscribers to sign up and get early access. If you have a goal in mind you want to achieve, donâ€™t overwhelm customers with different calls to action.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-call-to-action-example.webp" alt="newsletter call to action example" width="478" height="700" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-93046" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-call-to-action-example.webp 478w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-call-to-action-example-205x300.webp 205w" sizes="(max-width: 478px) 100vw, 478px" /></p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f680.png" alt="ðŸš€" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Need help creating click-worthy CTAs?</strong> Free guide downloadÂ &gt;&gt;Â <a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSLIQContentDLWebsite36CallToActionPhrases.html?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_36CallToActionPhrases_Download">The 42 Best Call to Action Phrases Ever (&amp; Why They Work)</a></p>
<div id="add-in-graphics-and-the-right-layout"></div>
<h3>4. Add in graphics and the right layout</h3>
<p>We live in a visual world, and people are visual creatures. <a href="https://news.mit.edu/2014/in-the-blink-of-an-eye-0116" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MIT research</a> shows that the human brain processes images in 13 to 33 milliseconds, 60,000 times faster than text. Graphics and layout add a visual punch to your newsletterâ€™s content. Theyâ€™re what make it scroll-worthy and not just another wall of text.</p>
<p>Graphics can help you break things up, highlight key points, or add personality. The right mix of text and visuals can guide your readerâ€™s eyes, keep them engaged, and help your message hit home without overwhelming them. Focus on simple, smart design, and expect more clicks and a bigger impact.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/user-generated-content">User-generated content</a> or authentic-looking visuals can be a great way to make your brand feel real. People can tell when somethingâ€™s been overly staged or looks too â€œperfect.â€ Authentic visuals make your brand feel more relatable and down-to-earth, which is exactly the vibe you want if youâ€™re building trust.</p>
<p>Take BANGS shoes, for example. They use natural-looking visuals that give the person-next-door vibe. Their messaging is aligned with their visualsâ€”focusing on the small things, staying true to yourself, and being unique.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-example-graphics.webp" alt="newsletter example with graphics" width="346" height="900" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-93045" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-example-graphics.webp 346w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-example-graphics-115x300.webp 115w" sizes="(max-width: 346px) 100vw, 346px" /></p>
<div id="choose-a-compelling-subject-line"></div>
<h3>5. Choose a compelling subject line</h3>
<p>The subject line serves as your virtual doormat. Itâ€™s the first thing people see when they receive your email. If you donâ€™t get the subject line right, everything else becomes a waste of time because your newsletter will end up in the trash or stuck in the pile of emails left unread.</p>
<p>But what makes a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/03/31/email-subject-lines">subject line</a> click-worthy? A solid email subject line should sum up the key message, the value, or the point of the email in a way that makes people want to click. Easier said than done, though, right? Here are some best practices to help you write attention-grabbing subject lines for your newsletter.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Keep it short.</strong> Data shows that <a href="https://audiencepoint.com/what-percentage-of-emails-are-opened-on-mobile-2023/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">50-60%</a> of email opens come from mobile devices. So, if you want to convey the right message, no matter the device the readers are using, keep your subject lines short.</li>
<li><strong>Use emojis (carefully).</strong> When done right, using emojis in your subject lines can grab attention and add personality. Today, emojis are an integral part of peopleâ€™s communication, which makes them relatable. The best part? They are great at triggering emotions. But remember, you should use them strategically and not overdo them. For some brands, such as Drunk Elephant, emojis are part of the brand personality, which makes them instantly pop up in the inbox.</li>
</ul>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-subject-line-emojis.webp" alt="newsletter subject line with emojis" width="900" height="556" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-93043" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-subject-line-emojis.webp 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-subject-line-emojis-480x297.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Spark curiosity.</strong> Curiosity may have killed the cat, but itâ€™s what gets your newsletter opened. Tease just enough to make people wonder whatâ€™s inside, but donâ€™t give it all away. But be carefulâ€”you have to find the right balance. Readers will think theyâ€™re getting clickbait if you make it too cryptic. Keep it intriguing, not frustrating.</li>
<li><strong>Use A/B testing.</strong> Thereâ€™s no shortcut or secret formula for a good-performing subject line. To find what works for your newsletter subscribers, test different variations, wording, length, or emojis, and see which gets the best response. The jewelry brand Maison Miru frequently uses <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/05/11/copywriting-ab-tests">A/B testing</a> for different subject lines.</li>
</ul>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/ab-test-newsletter-copy.webp" alt="newsletter a/b test example" width="730" height="694" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-93044" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/ab-test-newsletter-copy.webp 730w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/ab-test-newsletter-copy-480x456.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 730px, 100vw" /></p>
<div id="add-intriguing-preview-text"></div>
<h3>6. Add intriguing preview text</h3>
<p>The preview text is one of the most underrated elements of a newsletter, and itâ€™s often either left out or filled in with random text. And letâ€™s not forget the frequently used â€œview this email in your browser.â€ Preview text is like the backstage pass to your emailâ€“itâ€™s the little teaser that gives people a sneak peek at what&#8217;s inside. If your subject line got them curious, the preview text is your chance to seal the deal. Be clever, compelling, and make it count.</p>
<p>The Sill, a house plant delivery brand, uses newsletter preview text to create a sense of urgency and give readers a glimpse of what to expect. You can spot them using preview text such as â€œjust days left to saveâ€ or â€œlimited stock availableâ€ to urge plant lovers to seize the opportunity.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-copy-example-the-sill.webp" alt="newsletter preview text example from the sill" width="900" height="350" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-93048" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-copy-example-the-sill.webp 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-copy-example-the-sill-480x187.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<div id="close-out-with-your-footer-elements"></div>
<h3>7. Close out with your footer elements</h3>
<p>The footer of your newsletter is the last thing people see, but itâ€™s also your last chance to engage. Unfortunately, many small businesses treat the footer as an afterthought rather than a prime real estate for reinforcing your brand and giving readers other ways to connect with you.</p>
<p>Here are some of the essential elements of a newsletter footer:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Contact details:</strong> Include an email, physical address, or both, so people know how they can reach out.</li>
<li><strong>Email preferences/Unsubscribe link:</strong> You are legally obliged to include the unsubscribe link. So, if people want to opt out, make it easy for them to do so.</li>
<li><strong>Legal disclaimers:</strong> If you have any legal disclaimers, especially for your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/promotion-ideas">promotional newsletters</a>, include them in the footer to ensure compliance.</li>
<li><strong>Social media links:</strong> Give readers another way to connect with you and stay in the loop on your updates.</li>
</ul>
<p>The footer of your newsletter doesnâ€™t need to be boring. Take Smalls, the fresh human-grade cat food delivery brand, for example. They use the footer to add all the necessary elements while being playful and engaging. Even more important, they make it easy to reach out to them, whether through text or email.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-footer-example.webp" alt="newsletter footer example" width="489" height="600" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-93049" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-footer-example.webp 489w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/newsletter-footer-example-480x589.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 489px, 100vw" /></p>
<div id="best-practices-for-stand-out-newsletters"></div>
<h2>Bonus: 6 tips and best practices for newsletters that stand out</h2>
